We need to count perfect squares less than 2023 that are divisible by 5.

A perfect square is divisible by 5 if and only if its base is a multiple of 5 (i.e., 5, 10, 15, ...).

Let \(n\) be the smallest integer such that \(n \times 5 < \sqrt{2023}\). Then, \(n \leq \left\lfloor \frac{\sqrt{2023}}{5} \right\rfloor\).

Calculating \(\sqrt{2023} \approx 44.94\), so \(\frac{44.94}{5} \approx 8.988\). Thus, \(n \leq 8\).

This means \(n\) can be 1 through 8, giving 8 possible multiples of 5 up to 40 (since 40 is the largest multiple of 5 less than 44.94).

So there are 8 perfect squares (25, 100, 225, ..., 1600) below 2023 that are divisible by 5.

